---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "How to Manage Up Without Sounding Insecure as a New Manager";
const description = "New managers either go silent or over-explain to their boss. Learn a calm weekly update that builds trust without sounding insecure.";
const topic = "Managing Up";
const number = "06";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "Why New Managers Say Yes to Everything and Burn Out in 30 Days",
    "slug": "/articles/new-managers-say-yes/",
    "topic": "Capacity"
  },
  {
    "title": "Why New Managers Avoid Difficult Conversations and How to Stop",
    "slug": "/articles/difficult-conversations-new-manager/",
    "topic": "Conflict"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/manage-up-without-sounding-insecure/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/manage-up-without-sounding-insecure/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>How to Manage Up Without Sounding Insecure as a New Manager</h1>
<p>Managing up is not impressing your boss.</p>
<p>It is reducing their uncertainty about you.</p>
<p>New managers get this wrong in two directions. Either you go quiet because you don&#x27;t want to bother them, or you over-report every detail to prove you are on top of things. Both make you look insecure.</p>
<p>The fix is a short, steady signal. Same time, same format, every week.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>Week one, you want to look competent. So you send long updates. Screenshots, full context, five paragraphs explaining a small decision. You think thoroughness equals trust.</p>
<p>Your boss skims it. Or ignores it. Now you feel invisible, so you send more.</p>
<p>Or the opposite: you go silent. You don&#x27;t want to look like you need help. So you say nothing until there is a problem. Then the first time your boss hears from you, it is bad news. That trains them to worry about your area.</p>
<p>Another trap: asking for permission on everything. “Is it okay if I…? Do you think I should…?” That reads as hesitation, not collaboration. Your boss promoted you to decide, not to check in ten times a day.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>Your boss fills silence with assumptions. No news is not good news at the management level. No news is risk.</p>
<p>Over-reporting buries the signal. If every update is five paragraphs, your boss stops reading. Then they miss the one line that actually mattered.</p>
<p>You lose autonomy. If you keep asking for permission, your boss starts deciding for you. Then you complain about micromanagement you invited.</p>
<p>Trust erodes quietly. Not because you are doing bad work, but because your boss cannot see the work clearly.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is treating updates like a performance review.</p>
<p>You are not proving yourself every week. You are giving your boss a calm dashboard: here is where we are, here is what needs you, here is what is next.</p>
<p>Short beats thorough. Steady beats impressive.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Send one weekly update. Same day, same format. Four bullets. That is it.</p>
<p><strong>1. Wins / Progress.</strong> One or two lines. What moved. Numbers if you have them. “Shipped client onboarding flow. Response time down 18%.”</p>
<p><strong>2. Risks / Blockers.</strong> Be early and plain. “Hiring for analyst role is 2 weeks behind. May slip February deliverable.” No apology. Just signal.</p>
<p><strong>3. Decisions / Asks.</strong> What do you need from your boss? Be specific. “Need approval for $2k contractor, reply by Wednesday.” If you need nothing, write “No asks this week.” That is a strong signal.</p>
<p><strong>4. Next week.</strong> One line on focus. “Next week: closing Q1 plan, running 1:1s.”</p>
<p>Send it Friday at 3pm, every Friday. 120 words max. If your boss wants detail, they will ask. Most won’t. They want to know you see the field and you’ll flag early.</p>
<p>In meetings: lead with the headline, not the backstory. “We’re on track, one hiring risk, no asks.” Then stop. Let them pull detail if they want it.</p>
<p>If you made a mistake, report it fast and with the fix. “Missed the report deadline yesterday. Sent this morning, added a calendar reminder so it won’t repeat.” Short. Owned. Closed. That builds more trust than a perfect record with no transparency.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Insecure update:</strong> “Hi! Just wanted to give you a quick update, sorry to bother you, I know you’re busy, so basically we’ve been working really hard on the onboarding project and I think it’s going well, hopefully, here are all the details, let me know if I’m doing this right…”</p>
<p>Your boss stops reading at line two.</p>
<p><strong>Calm update:</strong> Subject: Weekly – Team Ops – Dec 12</p>
<ol>
<li>Progress: Onboarding flow shipped. Response time -18%.</li>
<li>Risk: Analyst hiring 2 weeks behind.</li>
<li>Ask: Approve $2k contractor, need by Wed.</li>
<li>Next: Q1 plan + 1:1s.</li>
</ol>
<p>Done. 35 words. Your boss reads the whole thing in 15 seconds and trusts you more.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Write your first 4-bullet update today.</strong> Progress, Risk, Ask, Next. Under 120 words. Send it.</li>
<li><strong>Pick a fixed send time.</strong> Friday 3pm. Put it in your calendar recurring. Consistency is the whole trick.</li>
<li><strong>Kill permission questions.</strong> Replace “Can I…?” with “I’m planning to do X unless you flag otherwise by Tuesday.” You’re informing, not asking.</li>
<li><strong>Report one risk early.</strong> Don’t wait until it’s a fire. Flag it while it’s small. Early bad news builds trust. Late bad news destroys it.</li>
<li><strong>In your next 1:1 with your boss, talk for 30% less.</strong> Lead with headlines. Pause. Let them ask. You’ll sound more senior instantly.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>Managing up is not about sounding confident. It is about being predictable.</p>
<p>Same update. Same time. Short. Early risks. Clear asks.</p>
<p>Your boss does not need a star. They need a stable signal that your area is handled. Give them that, weekly, and autonomy follows.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
